## Requirements
This example focuses on demonstrating correct `lookup_term` tool usage within the ConsentReader mode. The model must:

1. Read through the medical text and identify terms that a layperson would not understand.
2. Call `lookup_term` for each identified medical term (at least 3 calls).
3. After receiving tool results, integrate the definitions into a simplified explanation.
4. Use the [TERM: definition] annotation format in the final response.
5. Flag any [BINDING: ...] clauses found.

## Tool-call pattern
The model should demonstrate multiple sequential lookup_term calls:

Turn 1 (model): <tool_call>{"name": "lookup_term", "arguments": {"term": "first_term"}}</tool_call>
Turn 2 (model): <tool_result>{"name": "lookup_term", "result": {"term": "...", "plain_language_definition": "...", "citation": "..."}}</tool_result>
Turn 3 (model): <tool_call>{"name": "lookup_term", "arguments": {"term": "second_term"}}</tool_call>
... and so on.

The final model turn should provide the complete simplified text with all looked-up terms annotated.

## Output format
Return a JSON object with a single key "conversation" whose value is a list of turns.
Each turn has "role" (system | user | model) and "content".

Make the conversation natural — the user pastes a consent form and asks for help understanding it.
